{{Infobox court case | name = Prebble v Television New Zealand Ltd | court = [[Privy Council]] | date_filed = | image = Coat of arms of New Zealand.svg | date decided = 27 June 1994 | full name = Richard William Prebble Appellant v Television New Zealand Limited Respondents | citations = [1994] 3 NZLR 1 | judges = [[Henry Keith, Baron Keith of Kinkel|LORD KEITH OF KINKEL]], [[Lord Goff of Chieveley]], [[Nicolas Browne-Wilkinson, Baron Browne-Wilkinson|LORD BROWNE-WILKINSON]], [[Lord Mustill]], [[Michael Nolan, Baron Nolan|Lord Nolan]] | prior actions = | subsequent actions = | opinions = | transcripts = [http://www.nzlii.org/cgi-bin/sinodisp/nz/cases/NZPC/1994/4.html Privy Council ruling] | Keywords = negligence }}
'''Richard Prebble v Television New Zealand''' Ltd [1994] 3 NZLR 1 is a cited case in New Zealand regarding claims in [[defamation]] and the defence of [[parliamentary privilege]].<ref name="McLay">{{cite book |title=Butterworths Student Companion Torts |edition=6th |last1=McLay |first1=Geoff |publisher=LexisNexis |isbn=9781877511400|year=2010 |page=}}</ref>
==Background== [[Television New Zealand|TVNZ]]'s news programme "Frontline" aired a show highly critical of the fourth Labour government and minister [[Richard Prebble]]'s handling of state asset sales.
Prebble found this programme to be defamatory to him, and he sued TVNZ for defamation.
As part of TVNZ's defence, they tried to include statements made in Parliament by Prebble as evidence against his claim.
In response, Prebble applied to the courts that under Article 9 of the Bill of Rights 1688, any statements made in Parliament cannot be used in any court.
==Held== The [[Judicial Committee of the Privy Council|Privy Council]] ruled that that which had been said in Parliament was privileged, and could not be used by TVNZ as a defence against defamation allegations.
