'''Shareholders' protection''' is a contingency process detailing what will happen to a [[shareholder|shareholder's]] shares if the shareholder dies or becomes seriously ill.

In the interests of [[Economic security|financial security]], business stability, and continuity – particularly for [[Private company limited by shares|private limited companies]] where there may only be a small number of principal shareholders – it is essential to provide a safety net following the loss of a shareholder:
* Shares may go to the deceased’s family, which has no interest in the business and would prefer a cash sum
* The company or other shareholders will want to retain control by buying lost shares – but may not have the resources to do so
* The shares may be taken over by someone who does not share the company’s objectives – and may even be a competitor

