Multiple [[Symbol|symbols]] have been developed to represent [[vegetarianism]] and [[veganism]]. Several are used on food [[packaging and labeling|packaging]], including voluntary labels such as the [[Vegan Society]] trademark or the [[European Vegetarian Union|European Vegetarian symbol]]<ref name="Yacoubou">{{cite journal|last1=Yacoubou|first1=Jeanne|title=Vegetarian Certifications on Food Labels: What Do They Mean?|journal=Vegetarian Journal|date=2006|volume=17|issue=3|page=25|url=http://www.vrg.org/journal/vj2006issue3/2006_issue3_labels.php#vlft|accessdate=6 August 2017}}</ref><ref name="Basas">{{cite journal|last1=Basas|first1=Carrie Griffin|title="V" is for Vegetarian: FDA-Mandated Vegetarian Food Labeling|journal=Utah Law Review|date=2011|volume=4|page=1275|doi=10.2139/ssrn.1434040}}</ref> as well as the [[vegetarian and non-vegetarian marks]] mandated by the [[India]]n government.<ref name="act"/> Symbols may also be used by members of the vegetarian and vegan communities to represent their identities, and in the course of [[Animal rights movement|animal rights activism]].{{cn|date=August 2017}}
==Vegetarian symbols== ===Indian vegetarian mark=== [[File:Indian-vegetarian-mark.svg|right|80px]] {{main|Vegetarian and non-vegetarian marks}} Packaged food products sold in [[India]] are required to be labelled with a mandatory mark in order to be distinguished between vegetarian and non-vegetarian.<ref name="act">[http://www.fssai.gov.in/Portals/0/Pdf/Food%20Safety%20and%20standards%20(Packaging%20and%20Labelling)%20regulation,%202011.pdf Food Safety and Standards Authority of India. 'Food Safety and standards (Packaging and Labelling) regulations, 2011.']</ref><ref name="greendotter">[http://greendotter.com/dots.html Greendotter. 'Dots'.]</ref><ref>[http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-tamilnadu/article2593551.ece?css=print The Hindu. '6 months imprisonment to papad maker, sellers.']</ref><ref>[http://www.indianexpress.com/res/web/pIe/ie20010928/nat8.html ''Indian Express''. 'See brown logo on non-veg biscuits.']</ref><ref>[http://www.nios.ac.in/Secbuscour/26.pdf National Institute of Open Schooling. 'Wise Buying.']</ref> The symbol is in effect following the ''Food Safety and Standards (Packaging and Labelling) Act of 2006'', and received a mandatory status after the framing of the respective regulations (''Food Safety and Standards (Packaging and Labelling) Regulation'') in 2011.<ref name="act" /> According to the law, vegetarian food should be identified by a green symbol and non-vegetarian food with a brown symbol. ===V-label=== [[File:Vegetarian-mark.svg|80px|right]] The V-label, a V with a leaf, originated with the [[European Vegetarian Union]]. The V-Label is a standardized European vegetarian label from the EVU with the aim of easy identification of vegetarian products and services.{{cn|date=August 2017}} {{clear}} ==Vegan symbols== ===Enclosed V=== [[File:Vegetarian-movement symbol.png|100px|right]] The enclosed [[V]] (modeled after the [[enclosed A]] and the [[Anarchist symbolism#Egalitarian and equality symbol|enclosed–E]] symbols) is a popular vegan symbol, especially on [[social network]]s where it is represented by the Ⓥ symbol of the [[Enclosed Alphanumerics]] [[Unicode block]]. A "V" inside a circle is not used to label products as vegan nor should be relied upon to determine if a product is vegan. A Kosher organization (Vaad Hoeir of St. Louis) owns and uses a US trademark (certification mark) consisting of a V inside a circle.<ref name="veganfeed">{{cite web|url=http://www.vegansymbol.com/|title=Vegan Symbol|last=|first=|date=|website=vegansymbol.com|publisher=The Vegan Feed|access-date=28 June 2017}}</ref> {{clear}}
===Seedling emoji=== On internet forums and social networks, the [[seedling]] [[emoji]] 🌱 is sometimes used to symbolize veganism or vegan products.<ref name="veganfeed" /> {{clear}} ===Veganarchy symbol=== [[File:Veganarchism.svg|right|80px]] The [[Veganarchy]] symbol, first introduced in print in Brian A. Dominick's ''Animal Liberation and Social Revolution'' pamphlet in 1995, combines the Circle-V with the Circle-A of [[anarchist]] symbolism.<ref name="brian">Dominick, Brian. ''Animal Liberation and Social Revolution: A vegan perspective on anarchism or an anarchist perspective on veganism'', Critical Mess Media, 1995.</ref> {{clear}} === Vegan flag === [[File:Vegan flag cropped.jpg|150px|right]] The vegan flag<ref>{{cite web|title=The vegan flag website|url=http://www.veganflag.org}}</ref> was designed by a network group of graphic designers and activists from several countries. The group was opened by Gad Hakimi, a vegan activist and designer from [[Israel]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.plantbasednews.org/post/plantbased-vegan-flag-hoist-community|title=Graphic Design Team Unveils Veganism's First Ever Official Flag|access-date=2017-07-28|language=en|website=Plant Based News}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://vegnews.com/articles/page.do?pageId=9771&catId=1|title=New Flag Launches to Unite Vegans Across the Globe|date=16 July 2017|website=Veg News}}</ref> <ref>{{cite news|url=http://veggiesavvy.com/team-designers-launch-new-international-vegan-flag/|title=Team Of Designers Launch New International Vegan Flag|date=11 July 2017|work=Veggie Savvy|accessdate=28 July 2017}}</ref> intending to be a [[Glossary of vexillology#Flag identification symbols|civil flag]] to represent veganism. The flag consists of three blue and green triangles forming the letter V, the first letter in the word "vegan".
Originally, some members of the group suggested that animals should be featured on the flag, with red colours featuring prominently to symbolize the blood of slaughtered animals.<ref>{{cite news|title=The Vegan Flag: A Symbol of Unity or a Point of Conflict?|url=http://www.livekindly.co/the-vegan-flag/|accessdate=28 July 2017|work=LIVEKINDLY|date=16 July 2017}}</ref> However, the group eventually chose to make the flag about human–animal equality, not about animals themselves.<ref>{{cite news|title=The International vegan flag has launched|url=http://www.veganfoodandliving.com/international-vegan-flag-launched/|accessdate=28 July 2017|work=Vegan Food & Living|date=10 July 2017}}</ref> Inspired by the LGBT [[rainbow flag]], the flag was created in hopes of uniting animal rights organizations and activists. The colours white, green, and blue were chosen to represent the natural habitats of animals: sky, land, and sea. The letter V stands for Vegan, and is an inverted pyramid intended to symbolize the ability to do the impossible.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Pinto|first1=Goel|title=Designing the flag of veganism|url=http://www.kan.org.il/Radio/item.aspx?pid=5484|accessdate=28 July 2017|work="Gam Ken Tarbut" on Israeli television|publisher=[[Israeli Broadcasting Corporation#Radio|KAN Culture]]|date=24 June 2017|location=Minutes: 0:32-0:40|language=he|quote=The idea is a upside-down pyramid, to show that we can do the impossible. (min 0:37:55)|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170729010118/http://www.kan.org.il/Radio/item.aspx?pid=5484|archive-date=29 July 2017|dead-url=yes|df=dmy-all}}</ref>
