{{UKtaxation}}
The '''wallpaper tax''' was a [[property tax]] introduced in Great Britain in 1712, during the reign of [[Anne, Queen of Great Britain|Queen Anne]]. Patterned, printed, or painted [[wallpaper]] was initially taxed at 1[[Penny (British pre-decimal coin)|d]] per [[square yard]], rising to 1[[shilling|s]] (equivalent to £{{formatnum:{{Inflation|UK|0.05|1809|{{Inflation-year|UK}}|r=2}}}} as of {{Inflation-year|UK}}),{{Inflation-fn|UK|df=y}} by 1809. The tax was bypassed by purchasing untaxed plain paper and having it hand [[stencil]]ed. The tax was abolished in 1836.<ref>{{Harvnb|Parissien|1995|p=192}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://web.archive.org/web/20121114092240/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/property/3305112/On-the-level-building-tax.html |title= On the level: building tax |author= Jeff Howell |date= 31 Jul 2002 |work= |publisher= [[The Daily Telegraph|Telegraph.co.uk]] |accessdate=7 June 2010}}</ref>

